40|$|We examine {{systemic}} risk in <b>the</b> Chinese <b>banking</b> <b>system</b> by estimating <b>the</b> conditional value at risk (CoVaR), the marginal expected shortfall (MES), the systemic impact index (SII) and the vulnerability index (VI) for 16 listed banks in China. Although these measures show different patterns, our {{results suggest that}} {{systemic risk}} in <b>the</b> Chinese <b>banking</b> <b>system</b> decreased after <b>the</b> financial crisis, but started rising in 2014. Compared to <b>the</b> <b>banking</b> <b>systems</b> of Korea and the US, we find that Chinese banks {{are at greater risk}} according to the CoVaR, the SII and the VI approaches, but have the lowest MES...|$|R
25|$|Central banks {{manage this}} by {{buying and selling}} {{government}} bonds on the open market. On a day where there are excess reserves in <b>the</b> <b>banking</b> <b>system,</b> the central bank sells bonds and therefore removes reserves from <b>the</b> <b>banking</b> <b>system,</b> as private individuals pay for the bonds. On a day where {{there are not enough}} reserves in the system, the central bank buys government bonds from the private sector, and therefore adds reserves to <b>the</b> <b>banking</b> <b>system.</b>|$|E
